ikelihood (prior predictive). Despite these advances, two potentially conflicting desirable model specification features are evident from equations (3.1), (3.2), and (3.3): (1) analytical solutions and (2) the posterior distribution belonging to the same family as the prior distribution for a given likelihood. The latter is known as conjugate priors, a family of priors that is closed under sampling (Schlaifer and Raiffa 1961). These features are desirable because the former facilitates hypothesis testing and predictive analysis, while the latter ensures invariance in the prior-to-posterior updating process. Both features reduce computational burden. Although each of these features can be achieved independently –such as using improper priors for analytical tractability and broadly defining the family of priors for conjugacy– these features are in conflict. Fortunately, we can achieve both characteristics if we assume that the data-generating process follows a distribution function in the exponential family. That is, given a random sample \( oldsymbol{Y}=[Y_1 \ Y_2 \ \dots \ Y_N]^{	op}\), a probability density function \(p( oldsymbol{y}\mid  oldsymbol{	heta})\) belongs to the exponential family if it has the form: \[ egin{align} p( oldsymbol{y}\mid  oldsymbol{	heta})&amp;=\prod_{i=1}^N h(y_i) C( oldsymbol{	heta}) \exp\left\{\eta( oldsymbol{	heta})^{	op} oldsymbol{T}(y_i)ight\}	ag{3.4}\ &amp;=h( oldsymbol{y}) C( oldsymbol{	heta})^N\exp\left\{\eta( oldsymbol{	heta})^{	op} oldsymbol{T}( oldsymbol{y})ight\}
